# Global azrl config. Written to ~/.azure-profiles/azrl.conf by `azrl setup`
# (the installer runs `azrl setup --yes`). Re-run `azrl setup` any time to
# re-detect and rewrite it, or edit this copy by hand.
#
# azrl runs in one of two modes:
#
# LOCAL MODE — azrl runs on the same machine as the browser (laptop / WSL /
# desktop). The sign-in browser opens here directly and the OAuth callback loops
# back over localhost; no SSH bridge is used. Only BROWSER_CMD is required.
#
#   BROWSER_CMD=wslview      # wslview on WSL, open on macOS, xdg-open on Linux
#   BROWSER_HOST=localhost
#
# REMOTE MODE — azrl runs on a headless VM and pops the browser on your dev
# machine over SSH. BROWSER_CMD is the command that opens a URL on the dev
# machine; VM_SSH_HOST (this VM's SSH name) is auto-derived from $SSH_CONNECTION
# for the path-A paste line and is only needed for that fallback. Set
# BROWSER_HOST for zero-paste (path B), where the VM must be able to SSH to your
# machine.
BROWSER_CMD=xdg-open           # command that opens a URL on your dev machine
# BROWSER_HOST=my-laptop       # SSH name of your dev machine (set for zero-paste path B)
# VM_SSH_HOST=my-vm            # this VM's SSH name (derived from $SSH_CONNECTION; edit for NAT/jump hosts)
# DASHBOARD_POLL_SECS=3        # optional: dashboard refresh interval (seconds)
